&#8232;This course provides students with a survey of British poetry and poetics from the Restoration to the Modern period, including writers ranging from Aphra Behn and Alexander Popee to Thomas Hardy. It provides a sampling of eighteenth-century, Romantic, and Victorian poets.&#8232;

&#8232;Students agreed that this course “inspired them to think differently.” The majority of the students were not English majors, yet they felt that the class helped them to be more “cultured.” Students expressed that the dynamic of the class didn't always allow the quieter personalities to voice their thoughts because of the no-hand-raising arrangement. Students feel that they would have had more direction and a better understanding of assignments if there was a Blackboard account for the class.&#8232;&#8232;

Professor Cavitch was described as “intelligent and passionate about the course material.” One student said that the way Professor Cavitch speaks is “extremely artful and beautiful but also stimulating and eye opening.” Students noticed that the professor cares a lot about what he teaches.&#8232;&#8232;

The majority of the students in this introductory English class were underclassmen and non-English majors. There were a few English major seniors in the class who dominated the discussion. Those who knew less about English literature found the work sometimes difficult to understand.
